{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506667"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:45:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:45:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2554"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2554"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.01,0.01,0.31,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2554"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44026"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2554"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2554"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29007"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"2806"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2620"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2652"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9745"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15256"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44026"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old man presents to his general practitioner with a 12 month history of worsening back pain. The pain started insidiously and has been getting worse. It is most noticeable in the morning and improves during the day. His father had ankylosing spondylitis and the patient is concerned he might also be affected by this condition.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is the most diagnostically specific for ankylosing spondylitis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sacro-iliac joint X-ray","ESR (erythrocyte sediment rate)","CRP (C-reactive protein)","HLA-B27 gene testing","MRI spine"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of ankylosing spondylitis (AS) is complex and most of the time supported by a combination of all of the above testing. Initial investigations consist of blood testing as well as imaging.\u00a0Unfortunately, it typically takes 4-9 years from the onset of back pain until there is radiographic sacroiliitis. When this occurs the patient is deemed to have non-radiographic AS. Ankylosing spondylitis is synonymous with radiographic axial spondyloarthritis and by definition has at least bilateral Grade 2 sacroiliitis on plain X-ray. Hence for this specific question, X-ray of the SI joint is the most correct answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHLA-B27\u003C/strong\u003E is a useful test to aid in the diagnosis of AS, as it is positive in 85-90% of patients with AS, but it is also positive in 5-15% of the general population. It is more useful in diagnosing AS in white populations as it has a sensitivity of 90% in this population group. Therefore, it is used to support the diagnosis and help to determine the likelihood of an individual with inflammatory back pain having AS, but it is not very specific for AS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EESR and CRP\u003C/strong\u003E are both markers of inflammation and are raised in 50-70% of patients with AS, but they can also be raised in other inflammatory conditions hence is not specific to AS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImaging demonstrating sacroiliitis is the main stay for the diagnosis of AS. Although \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful, not all patients will have evidence of sacroiliitis on MRI, as it is more sensitive in early disease than in patients with chronic sacroiliitis and is generally sought out when patients have non-radiographic AS (their initial X-ray is negative). In AS and in non-radiographic axial spondyloarthritis sacroiliitis is present, and will be detected by MRI in both, but on X-ray only in AS. All patients with AS will have MRI changes as there will not be plain Xray changes without MRI changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe mainstay for the diagnosis of AS to be established is the presence of changes on \u003Cstrong\u003EX-ray\u003C/strong\u003E of the sacroiliac joints, as this is the most specific investigation for AS along side a supportive clinical history suggesting the diagnosis (such as back pain for \u0026gt;3 months, age \u0026lt;45 years old). In young patients with a short history, MRI scanning is helpful in assessing early cartilage abnormalities and bone marrow oedema, but where the symptoms have chronicity, a plain X-ray will provide adequate diagnostic information.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A sacro-iliac joint X-ray is the most specific investigation and first line for suspected ankylosing spondylitis."],"references":["Golder, V \u0026 Schachna, L 2013. Ankylosing spondylitis: an update. Australian Family Physician, Volume 42, No. 11, November 2013, Pages 780-784. Access at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2013/november/ankylosing-spondylitis/.","McVeigh CM, Cairns AP. Diagnosis and management of ankylosing spondylitis. BMJ. 2006;333(7568):581-585. doi:10.1136/bmj.38954.689583.DE","West, S, 2014. Rheumatology Secrets. Chapter 34: Axial Spondyloarthropathies. Mosby."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29007"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2554"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29007"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-05T09:28:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-10T19:56:10+09: